body:
There are two things related to documentation examples that I think are weird and not intended.

#### `lib.rs` in crate `foo`
```rust
/// # Examples
/// 
/// This is working:
///
/// ```
/// use foo::Foo;
/// ```
///
/// However, this is not:
///
/// ```
/// extern crate foo;
///
/// use foo::Foo;
/// ```
/// 
pub struct Foo;
```

The latter one gives me

```
error[E0432]: unresolved import `foo::Foo`
 --> <anon>:4:5
  |
3 | use foo::Foo;
  |     ^^^^^^^^^^ Maybe a missing `extern crate foo;`?
```

when running `cargo test`.

Probably that's some technical thing, however the error message should still tell that you should not use `extern crate` for your own library.

More general, using `extern crate` in documentation code does not work at all for me. If I want to `use` a symbol from an external library, I'll also get `Maybe a missing 'extern crate external_library'` with and without the `extern crate` line.

### Version

The provided error messages are from version `rustc 1.16.0-nightly (4ecc85beb 2016-12-28)`.
`rustc 1.14.0 (e8a012324 2016-12-16)`(stable) suggests using `self::external_library::foo` instead.
